Programming can be defined as the practice of encoding instructions to be carried out by some actor, but we usually only think about programs that target computers: "computer programs". When our programs target humans we call them "how-to guides".

So, there will never be a $1500 course on knowledge management in Methodable. Instead there will be Methodable programs titled "manage my knowledge" that effortlessly guide the user through all of the same processes instantly and for free. And there will be communities of human program developers who work together to make these programs (knowledge management or otherwise) more complex and powerful than any workflow that could possibly be held within an individual's brain.

Containers for collecting nouns are not sufficient for getting work done because the work we do is not nouns. The work we do is verbs (and verb phrases). We do not "to-do", we just "do". We do not "biology notes", we "review biology notes". Noun-management tools provide the workspace and expect the user to bring their own workflow, but humans are terrible at managing workflows without external aides (which is why, for example, using checklists to remind doctors of simple tasks reduced deaths in surgery by as much as 47%). Even the most well-practices and methodical people will always be constrained by their own ability to remember and execute their methods.

Metaprograms are one of the most exciting use cases of Methodable. They are like templates but way cooler. They are generic processes that help you generate personal processes, and as long as the original program is tuned correctly, the process of evolving and reflecting upon one's methods can proceed iteratively while remaining completely guided.

There is no reason that we couldn't have tools for delivering instructions to humans that are as powerful and expressive as our computer-programming tools. Those tools could revolutionize the ways we interact with computers and the ways we think. The first step is to call them "human-programming tools".
